<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-10-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-10-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="544" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d544">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 855.48/672a</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the British Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRSCA1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Spring Rice</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-10-08">
                                    <hi rend="italic">October 8, 1917</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Ambassador</hi>: The Secretary of the
                            Treasury has transmitted to me a copy of instructions which have been
                            sent to the Collector of Customs, relative to examinations of vessels
                            departing from this country laden with Belgian Relief cargoes, and I am
                            forwarding herewith a copy of the instructions in question.<note n="1" xml:id="d544fn1">Not printed.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>It is understood that in consideration of this examination undertaken by
                            the Treasury Department, which was the result of an informal arrangement
                            between the Embassy and officials of that Department, no further
                            examinations of supplies for Belgian Relief work will be made at
                            Halifax. I should be pleased to receive from you a confirmation of the
                            arrangement proposed.</p>
                        <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>